g, as well as ordinances, regulations, and administrative, constitutional, and criminal law. In the contributions to this volume, police power emerges as a rich and flexible concept that offers a broader functional context to explain the operation of governmental institutions. The essays reveal connections across the history of government, across systems of government within a particular state, and comparatively, across different states and levels of government. The comprehensive scope and boundless ambition of police power, the very characteristics that rest uneasily with traditional conceptions of the liberal state, make it a uniquely useful platform for interdisciplinary and international inquiries into fundamental questions of government and law.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCriminal lawzUnited States. 0aCriminal law. 0aPolice powerzUnited States. 0aPolice power. 0aPolicezUnited States. 0aPolice. 4aLaw -- Criminal Law. 4aPolitics. 7aLAW / Criminal Law / General.2bisacsh1 aDubber, Markus D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubber, Markus D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKann, Mark E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevi, Ron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNovak, William J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRamsay, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoss, Jacqueline E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSklansky, David Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTomlins, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aValverde, Mariana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul